00024Cr 2               ;;
00024Cr 2               ;;                          RTC / Jiffy Tick
00024Cr 2               ;;
00024Cr 2               
00024Cr 2               
00024Cr 2               
00024Cr 2               rtc:
00024Cr 2               
00024Cr 2               
00024Cr 2               ;;  RTC stores ticks at 10ms intervals into a 4-byte (32 bit) value
00024Cr 2               ;;
00024Cr 2               ;;  as each byte rolls over the next one is incremented
00024Cr 2               ;;  on a tick that doesn't roll over the TIME OF DAY
00024Cr 2               ;;  is updated
00024Cr 2               
00024Cr 2  E6 rr          inc TICKS
00024Er 2  D0 0A          bne inc_MET
000250r 2  E6 rr          inc TICKS + 1
000252r 2  D0 06          bne inc_MET
000254r 2  E6 rr          inc TICKS + 2
000256r 2  D0 02          bne inc_MET
000258r 2  E6 rr          inc TICKS + 3
00025Ar 2               
00025Ar 2               ;;
00025Ar 2               ;;  Every time it's called we increment the "hundredths of a second" byte
00025Ar 2               ;;
00025Ar 2               ;;  When there's been 100 x 10ms (i.e. 1 second) we increment the seconds
00025Ar 2               ;;
00025Ar 2               ;; We keep the times in single digits, SECONDS, TEN_SECONDS, MINUTES,
00025Ar 2               ;; TEN_MINUTES etc.... to make it easy to display
00025Ar 2               ;; The values are stored in RAM as binary values, and need to be converted to
00025Ar 2               ;; ASCII characters when they are displayed on LCD
00025Ar 2               ;;
00025Ar 2               ;;  The basis of this routine comes from http://wilsonminesco.com/6502interrupts/#2.1
00025Ar 2               ;;
00025Ar 2               inc_MET:
00025Ar 2  E6 rr          inc CENTISEC
00025Cr 2  A5 rr          lda CENTISEC
00025Er 2  C9 64          cmp #100
000260r 2  30 40          bmi end_MET
000262r 2  64 rr          stz CENTISEC
000264r 2               
000264r 2  E6 rr          inc SECONDS
